\begin{abstract}
This manuscript develops a four-dimensional fast-slow dynamical system for the stable boundary layer (SBL) using Geometric Singular Perturbation Theory (GSPT). The model couples fast turbulent kinetic energy evolution with slow atmospheric rotational and surface thermodynamic variables and is analyzed through its critical-manifold geometry and reduced-layer decomposition. By introducing nonlinear Kolmogorov dissipation and a smooth activation gate in the fast subsystem, we show that regime transitions are organized by a non-degenerate fold catastrophe together with a boundary transcritical recovery mechanism. Compact normally hyperbolic subsets of the constraint set structure the slow flow, while collapse and re-ignition thresholds map directly to forcing diagnostics tied to shear-stratification competition. Eddy diffusivities are parameterized as functions of prognostic turbulent kinetic energy, while reduced slow dynamics are obtained from the equilibrium TKE manifold in the singular limit $\varepsilon\to 0$. The governing equations reproduce Blackadar-type inertial oscillations without prescribing them phenomenologically. This closure generalizes classical 1.5-order TKE models by replacing instantaneous equilibrium assumptions with explicit fast-slow dynamics, thereby distinguishing the framework from both conventional prognostic TKE transport closures and algebraic equilibrium closures. The framework provides a geometric interpretation of SBL transitions across parameter regimes; {{dataset}} is used here as the reference parameter set for generated diagnostics and baseline tables.
\end{abstract}
